I was trying to find a silent mouse exercise wheel that could use a standard 608 skateboard wheel bearing. I wasn't able to find one that fit on my print bed so I decided to design my own. 
My design was inspired by MrFreakman's design, the Hamsterrad (Hamster Wheel). I loved the look of his design and actually printed it but found it to be very noisy due to the lack of a bearing.
Once completed you will need a M5x20mm countersunk cap screw and washer to lock the wheel firmly in place and lock it against the shoulder on the mouse wheel base. Do not over tighten!
With regards to using supports on this print. They will only be used for the horizontal part of the bearing cavity and will remove easily.
I hope you and your rodent friends enjoy this model

description.text:
10/23/2015 - Much chaos ensued, files got rage-deleted, models were re-built. If you have downloaded previous-versions of things, I would delete them and get the new ones (as of today). Here is what's happened
  • Rebuilt the Needle using newly learned 123D Design tricks. Also added a "pointy" version in case people want to follow canon.
  • Rebuilt Vial (part 1, and 2 because I didn't have the original 123dx files (doh).
  • Rebuilt the Clip because I wasn't happy with the proportions (was expected)
  • Built the Grip to proportions that I liked. Should probably use Vial pt2 to cut any overlap (should fit as-is, but wouldn't hurt to make sure ;) )
  • Cut the Collar using Clips, and Grip to make assembly/gluing easier :D
  • Began modeling the handle.... this is going to be a huge PITA.
    • Again ALL original (123D Design) design files are available... if I missed one please let me know :D Much love, Banjo 10/22/2015 - Took another good look at the in-game model, and extended the "screw" from the clip to the collar surface. Still need to try assembling the parts to see if they even fit together (lol) :D Added a NEW version of the collar which includes the chamfered edges (horray!). I modeled it to 30mm L x 30mm OD. The ID is 20mm and probably needs to be changed to match the front vial, and maybe add 0.5-1mm to allow for sanding/final adjustments when finishing. Sorry for the spammy updates >.< 10/21/2015 - Ignore previous statement :D. Just learned about "Loft" function. Hours of headache gone! First draft of clip is now attached (with matching 123D Design file). Need to make sure it mates properly with collar, and the rear-half of the vial. Also not sure about the 5mm thickness, but we'll see! --Previously--
    Slowly building the Borderlands 2 Health Now! (Aka Feel Good Needle) from Borderlands 2. WORK IN PROGRESS!!

- Fix Collar length to 55% of vial_pt1 length
- Re-do Collar in proper order (tube > chamfer > grove)
- Make Clip (the bit on front that screws in)
- Make Grip (the bit on the bottom)
  • Make Handle (the bit on top)
  • Decide if I -really- want to hinge the handle bit... (Edit: Yeah... I really do want to make it a spring-loaded hinge... but how...hrm)


    • -- IGNORE THIS! --
    It is for my notes only >.>
    Collar Dimensions
    Height: 50mm
    OD: 36mm
    ID: 28mm
    Grooves: 1mm deep x 2mm wide

Screen Capture taken from the Internet Steps Step 1) Find good resolution photo
Step 2) Dissect image into bits
Step 3) (Optional) overthink EVERYTHING, then faff around in at least five different 3D tools.
Step 4) Learn how to use TinkerCAD, and 123Design properly!
Step 5) Git working! Software Used Collar was originally created in TinkerCAD

Either way I will include original source files when possible

title: Raspberry Pi A/B mount for 20x20mm Misumi Aluminum Extrusion

description.text:
Since I use OctoPi/OctoPrint to control my 3D printer, I wanted to create a mount for the Raspberry Pi so that I could keep all my electronics under the floor of the printer. I also run a voltage regulated that takes the 12V that my controller board runs off and steps it down to the 5V for the pi. That way, all I need to do to print is just plug in a single power cable, navigate a browser to the OctoPrint page, and voila!
While this was created for Jasonatepaint's Aluminum Extrusion Ultimaker V2, it should obviously work with any 20x20 aluminum extrusion.
It also should be noted that (as far as I know) this only fits the original RPi's (the model A and the model B). I've uploaded the .ipt Inventor file if you want to make any tweaks to it.

Technology is allowing artists to break through historic restrictions as artists are no longer limited to traditional craft techniques to produce intricate physical objects. The creative goal of project materialize is to demonstrate that 3D printers are no longer a cold technology limited to engineering professionals, but can trigger the perfect combination of the material and spiritual. Better... I don't know....I just wanted the end-effector to stay horizontal in all positions and I couldn't get that with the original design.
Software I use smoothieware but they don't have any robot arm kinematics... so far I'm using the Cartesian kinematics so the coordinate system gets very screwed up.

Other than that I didn't change anything... except shortening two of the 6mm pipes.
I bought the beefiest NEMA17s I could find but they don't play well with the DRV8825 drivers as the coil resistance is low so the current around the low current microsteps get too large. I will add some diodes in series to fix this later on. I saw someone recommending this if the microsteps gets uneven and mine does. I have a Kossel mini with Kysan steppers and they behave fine. description.text: There are a couple of boxes like this on thingiverse, but neither has lids and so I set out to design my own. The boxes were designed by makeabox.io, and everything else done in Corel DRAW. The lid hinges come from my previous Thing, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:923246. It takes maybe half an hour to cut, but forever (allow 3 hours) to build. The hinges are joined by short lengths of 3mm dowel, but I'd probably cut some square lengths of wood/MDF to use in future versions, and that would mean changing the size of the washers and probably the bars. You can put the washers inside the box, or on the outside of the linking bars. It's meant for 1/8" (3.2mm) material, but can be scaled. I've put the parts of the outer sides and top together so that you can easily add engravings, but there might be some duplicated lines.

description.text:
This is a set of parts to make a G scale /1/24 scale station canopy, a bench and a station lamp. The station canopy is based on old British station canopies, and is modular. Parts all have dovetails so that they can be printed separately and then assembled. I assembled mine and glued with acetone.
I added a plastic "slate" roof to mine, but have not painted it for the photo. Looking at the photo I think that perhaps the support pillar should have been slightly further recessed into the station. The station lamp is designed to use 4mm brass tube and to take a small "pea" bulb to light it.
The height of the lamps is of course, determined by how long you make the tube!
There is also a more modern Octagonal lamp in the 123DX file. The people in the photo are standard LGB people from the train sets.
The "simple station" STL is not for printing, but helps show how everything comes together

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Notes: I print with rafts as I find I get better prints. I made the lamp in "transparent" ABS, and although its more translucent than transparent, it does give a better lamp effect than white ABS.
Paint the lamp carefully.
The bench is printed on its back.
The canopy supports are not symmetric, they have a flat back so that they can be printed easily.
The arms fit the support and then hold up the canopy via the canopy_support_section.
The canopy_support_section is the only part I printed with supports. The rest should print without supports.
The "peg" at the bottom of the main pillar should fit a 8mmm hole in the station floor. My station has a floor made from left over bathroom wall tiles.
If possible, arrange the canopy parts for printing so that the little diamond details face inwards. This makes it easier to peel them off the raft afterwards.
When assembling the canopy, a little acetone on the dovetails during FINAL assembly helps as they melt slightly and then smoothly fit, and then weld.

My boss just loved this "motivational picture" and used to add it on his presentations. He was retiring last week, so I made a desktop 3D version of it for him. I am sure he will put it on his desk when he comes back out of retirement....as they always do.
I do not really expect anyone to make another one, but maybe serve as inspriration on how to make something similar. See my instructions below on how I made and finished it. This object is based on this (probably copyrighted) poster seen at: http://www.despair.com/consistency.html

I modeled the base and target and printed them out on my Thing-o-matic in black ABS.  The reverse lettering is created by filling in the letters with tinted Bondo automotive filler then sanding it flush after curing.  I then sanded the base with progressively finer wet sandpaper upto 600 grit and used a little plastic polish.  The base came out really nice.  I tried doing some acetone wiping and vapor polishing, but I found that the wet sanding produced a superior finish in this case.   I filled the hollow bottom of the base with rocks and epoxy to weight it down and give it a hefty feel.  Then applied a circle of stick-on cork to protect the bottom.  The target was painted white then I used some acrylic paints to color it in.  I used some wood scraps to make the "frame" and purchased some darts to use as the arrows.
